SIMPLE: sip
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sip
<hw>Sip</hw> <pr>(s⟦icr⟧p)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Sipped</conjf> <pr>(s⟦icr⟧pt)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Sipping</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>sippen</ets>;
akin to OD. <ets>sippen</ets>, and AS. <ets>s<?/pan</ets> to sip, suck
up, drink. See <er>Sup</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
drink or imbibe in small quantities; especially, to take in with the
lips in small quantities, as a liquid; <as>as, to <ex>sip</ex>
tea</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Every herb that <xex>sips</xex> the dew.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To draw into the mouth; to suck up; <as>as, a bee
<ex>sips</ex> nectar from the flowers</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To taste the liquor of; to drink out of.</def>
<mark>[Poetic]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They skim the floods, and <qex>sip</qex> the purple flowers.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sip</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sip
<hw>Sip</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To drink a small quantity; to take a
fluid with the lips; to take a sip or sips of something.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[She] raised it to her mouth with sober grace;⟦br⟧
Then, <qex>sipping</qex>, offered to the next in place.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sip</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Sip
<hw>Sip</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of sipping; the
taking of a liquid with the lips.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A small draught taken with the lips; a slight
taste.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>One <qex>sip</qex> of this⟦br⟧
Will bathe the drooping spirits in delight⟦br⟧
Beyond the bliss of dreams.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>sip</qex> is all that the public ever care to take from
reservoirs of abstract philosophy.</q> <rj><qau>De
Quincey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sipage</ent>⟦br⟧
